#: of numpy.inexact:2
msgid ""
"Abstract base class of all numeric scalar types with a (potentially) inexact "
"representation of the values in its range, such as floating-point numbers."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.scalars.rst:179
msgid ""
"Inexact scalars are printed using the fewest decimal digits needed to "
"distinguish their value from other values of the same datatype, by judicious "
"rounding. See the ``unique`` parameter of `format_float_positional` and "
"`format_float_scientific`."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.scalars.rst:184
msgid ""
"This means that variables with equal binary values but whose datatypes are "
"of different precisions may display differently::"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.scalars.rst:187
msgid ""
">>> f16 = np.float16(\"0.1\")\n"
">>> f32 = np.float32(f16)\n"
">>> f64 = np.float64(f32)\n"
">>> f16 == f32 == f64\n"
"True\n"
">>> f16, f32, f64\n"
"(0.1, 0.099975586, 0.0999755859375)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.scalars.rst:195
msgid ""
"Note that none of these floats hold the exact value :math:`\\frac{1}{10}`; "
"``f16`` prints as ``0.1`` because it is as close to that value as possible, "
"whereas the other types do not as they have more precision and therefore "
"have closer values."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../reference/arrays.scalars.rst:200
msgid ""
"Conversely, floating-point scalars of different precisions which approximate "
"the same decimal value may compare unequal despite printing identically:"
msgstr ""

